posts.name: Michael Havrylyuk
posts.cooked: I am trying to use Robonaut’s Coral AI model on Roboflow. However, I am having trouble understanding how to download the model from the website in the rknn format that Photon Vision expects. Some help on how that process works would be appreciated. Also why has no one just posted the rknn file for an orange pi? seems like that would have been done already but it hasn’t.

posts.name: Dan
posts.cooked:
It’s a strangely esoteric process, which requires a lot of setup and special installs to sort out, and mostly requires a linux system to be even remotely effective. Bug your programming mentors at practice, we can help run you through it. We haven’t built 118’s model, but we have built Frogforce’s.

The actual results when we tested it were pretty mixed; It’d work most of the time, but with relatively high false positive rates, and could miss coral of particular alignments.

posts.name: Ezra
posts.cooked: @levyishai also has a really accurate model and I’m almost sure he can help you with setting it up
The Robonaut’s Coral AI model on Roboflow doesn’t work very well.  We abandoned it when we moved on to using the neural network models provided by limelight on their downloads page.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: There’s also some models floating around in the photonvision discord that you could check out.  To the best of my knowledge, Roboflow doesn’t actually have an RKNN model, they just have yolo.  You then have to go through the conversion steps to use it with photonvision.

Ultralytics has the option to export as an rknn if you train the model locally on the roboflow data, i don’t think roboflow will let you export the model directly

https://docs.ultralytics.com/integrations/rockchip-rknn/

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: Yes, that’s correct. Do note that the model you will be exporting using ultralytics won’t be quantized, which can affect performance.
